        <p>If you're reading this, you're probably somewhere between worried and overwhelmed. That's normal. Custody is one of the most stressful things a single dad goes through, but it gets a lot less scary once you understand how the pieces fit together. This is the plain-English version.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The single most important thing:</strong> courts decide custody based on the <em>best interests of the child</em> — not on the parent's gender. Being a present, stable, involved father is what counts, and it counts a lot.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>The two kinds of custody</h2>
        <p>Almost every custody decision comes down to two separate questions, and you can have one without the other:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Legal custody</strong> — who gets to make the big decisions: schooling, medical care, religion. This is often shared ("joint legal custody") even when the kids live mostly with one parent.</li>
          <li><strong>Physical custody</strong> — where the kids actually live and sleep. This can be split many ways, from equal time to alternating weekends.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Common arrangements</h2>
        <p>There's no one "normal" schedule, but a few patterns come up again and again:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Joint physical custody</strong> — roughly equal time, often a 50/50 or 60/40 split. Increasingly common where both parents are stable and live close.</li>
          <li><strong>Primary custody with visitation</strong> — kids live mainly with one parent; the other has a set visitation schedule (every other weekend plus a weeknight is typical).</li>
          <li><strong>Sole custody</strong> — one parent has both legal and physical custody. Less common, usually tied to safety concerns.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How to give yourself the best shot</h2>
        <p>You can't control everything, but you can control how prepared and steady you look to a court:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Be involved now.</strong> School pickups, doctor's appointments, homework, bedtime. Document it.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep a calm paper trail.</strong> Save messages and keep a simple log of your time with the kids. Stay civil in writing — assume a judge may read it.</li>
          <li><strong>Have a real plan.</strong> Stable housing, a workable schedule, and childcare lined up.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't go it alone.</strong> Even one consultation with a family-law attorney can change how you approach the whole thing.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p>Can't afford a big firm? You have options — legal aid, pro se ("self-represented") resources, and low-cost clinics for dads. See the resources in the <a href="{{ '/#legal' | url }}">Legal section</a> on the homepage.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>A note on the hard days</h2>
        <p>Custody fights can make you feel like you're being judged as a father. You're not less of a dad because this is hard. Show up, stay steady, and get the right help — that's the whole game.</p>

        <p><em>This page is a starting draft and is general information, not legal advice. Laws vary by state — talk to a qualified family-law attorney about your situation.</em></p>
